---
import Docs from '../../layouts/Docs.astro';
import { keys } from '../../lib/keybindings';

const toc = [
  { id: 'implicit', text: 'Implicit Detection', level: 2 },
  { id: 'osc8', text: 'OSC 8 Hyperlinks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'planned', text: 'Planned', level: 2 },
];
---

<Docs title="URL Patterns" toc={toc}>
  <h2 id="implicit">Implicit Detection</h2>
  <p>ori-term scans terminal output for URLs and turns them into clickable links. Detection covers the four schemes the parser ships today:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>http://</code> and <code>https://</code></li>
    <li><code>ftp://</code></li>
    <li><code>file://</code></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Trailing punctuation (<code>.</code> <code>,</code> <code>;</code> <code>:</code> <code>!</code> <code>?</code> <code>)</code>) is trimmed from the match so a URL at the end of a sentence works without selecting the period.</p>
  <p>Hold <kbd>{keys.urlModifier}</kbd> over a detected URL to underline it. <kbd>{keys.openUrl}</kbd> opens it in your default browser.</p>

  <h2 id="osc8">OSC 8 Hyperlinks</h2>
  <p>Applications can emit explicit hyperlinks using the OSC 8 escape sequence. These render as clickable links without regex detection. Examples of CLI tools that emit OSC 8:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>ls --hyperlink</code> — file links (GNU coreutils)</li>
    <li><code>gcc</code> / <code>clang</code> — diagnostic location links</li>
    <li><code>ripgrep</code> with <code>--hyperlink-format</code></li>
  </ul>
  <p>OSC 8 link targets follow the same modifier-click semantics as detected URLs.</p>

  <h2 id="planned">Planned</h2>
  <p>Custom <code>[[url_patterns]]</code> blocks — user-defined regex matchers with capture-group URL templates and configurable actions (open / copy / select) — are on the roadmap and not yet wired through the config loader. Other planned scheme additions: file paths, IP addresses, git commit hashes, and email addresses. Track on the <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '')}/roadmap`}>roadmap</a>.</p>
</Docs>
